2
00:00:14,752 --> 00:00:22,635
So Root is a board game that was released in 2018, and it's a highly asymmetric strategy

3
00:00:22,675 --> 00:00:22,916
game.

4
00:00:24,576 --> 00:00:27,337
So in the core game, you can play on one of four sides.

5
00:00:27,797 --> 00:00:30,118
You can play the cats, the birds...

6
00:00:31,068 --> 00:00:36,511
The Woodland Alliance, which is a kind of ragtag band of mice and foxes

7
00:00:36,531 --> 00:00:41,294
and other small woodland creatures who are rising up against tyranny.

8
00:00:42,475 --> 00:00:46,877
And then there's the Vagabond, which is this wily raccoon adventure

9
00:00:46,957 --> 00:00:48,778
that traipses through the forest.

10
00:00:51,100 --> 00:00:54,442
And so I'm going to be talking about our experience

11
00:00:55,102 --> 00:00:58,524
doing usability and user experience work on Root.

12
00:00:59,799 --> 00:01:05,360
And in case you're not familiar with those terms, basically usability is making sure

13
00:01:05,440 --> 00:01:11,402
that people have an easy time learning the game, and then playing the game, using the

14
00:01:11,442 --> 00:01:16,683
game's components, and just generally making sure that they have a good experience from

15
00:01:17,343 --> 00:01:20,224
opening up the box to closing it up again.

16
00:01:22,253 --> 00:01:26,916
And so I'm going to go over some usability and user experience positives.

17
00:01:28,257 --> 00:01:33,341
But most of this talk is going to be about the failures and specifically the lessons

18
00:01:33,381 --> 00:01:37,564
that we learn from those failures and what you can take away into your own work.

19
00:01:40,586 --> 00:01:43,748
And so I'm going to start out by talking about icon testing.

20
00:01:44,869 --> 00:01:46,210
And so, you know, and.

21
00:01:47,032 --> 00:01:53,339
most games you have a lot of iconography, a lot of illustrations, just a lot of stuff that helps

22
00:01:53,479 --> 00:01:59,305
orient people in different parts of the game. And so when you have all of these icons, you want to

23
00:01:59,345 --> 00:02:05,352
make sure that the icons are doing their job, you know, that they're recognizable, that people

24
00:02:05,372 --> 00:02:08,715
understand what they mean, and that they get the job done.

25
00:02:10,701 --> 00:02:15,922
And so this icon is an icon that used to be in root,

26
00:02:16,102 --> 00:02:17,503
but is no longer.

27
00:02:17,523 --> 00:02:22,504
And the reason why we got rid of this icon

28
00:02:23,064 --> 00:02:25,624
was because when we did icon testing on it,

29
00:02:25,705 --> 00:02:27,945
you know, when we brought this up to people,

30
00:02:28,145 --> 00:02:30,826
either by itself or in a group with our other icons,

31
00:02:31,366 --> 00:02:33,466
and we asked people what they thought it was,

32
00:02:35,067 --> 00:02:36,407
they would give back all sorts of

33
00:02:37,747 --> 00:02:41,949
weird answers like, oh, it's a teapot, or it's a ghost, or it's a monkey.

34
00:02:43,530 --> 00:02:49,193
And these are all, of course, perfectly valid perceptions. You know, people can only see what

35
00:02:49,233 --> 00:02:54,916
they see, but it's not the perception that we had hoped for because this is meant to be a mouse.

36
00:02:56,777 --> 00:03:03,980
And so because of the user testing that we did on this icon, we knew that we had to change it

